Yelp reviews can be unreliable, but a closer look at the Yelp reviews from February 9, 2017 through February 18, 2018 shows that Yelp's fake reviews do exist. First, a little back story:
1) This review contains a lie. The first-ever Yelp review for a restaurant was fake. The Yelp employee who wrote the fake review never sent it, and promoted the review instead to "happy customers".
2) The first-ever Yelp post endorsing a restaurant does not exist. Yelp promoted the fake review with the following text:
"Happy customers" tell lies in nearly every review they write. There are 58 real reviews for La Calenda Real estate alone.
3) The fake Yelp reviews were actually written by an employee of the restaurant chain. That employee is no longer with the company and the Yelp reviews are now fictitious.
4) The Yelp reviews are now part of a larger problem for Yelp. Its reviews section has become a repository of lies and half-truths. Bad reviews surface when users search for a restaurant on multiple platforms, and the reviews in those reviews clutter the sites' search results. That in turnens other users to pester the business for more reviews, increasing the likelihood of those reviews turning out to be false.

They simply give the information in the review to the end user, so the reviewer does not have to manually review every single review.
